# 六、Band 8 升级版（建议精读）

The two maps compare the layout of Porth Harbour in 2000 with its current appearance.

Overall, the harbour has undergone significant redevelopment in order to accommodate tourism and leisure activities. While several original facilities, including the dock and passenger ferries, have remained intact, a variety of tourist-oriented amenities and commercial features have been introduced.

In 2000, the western side of the harbour was primarily occupied by functional harbour facilities, including a marina for private yachts, a fishing boat area, two car parks and a building containing showers and toilets. A road ran along the southern coastline towards the lifeboat station. In the southeastern corner, there was a disused castle beside a public beach. Meanwhile, a dock used by passenger ferries was located in the centre of the harbour, while another public beach occupied the northern section.

Today, however, the harbour has been transformed into a more tourism-focused area. One notable change is that the positions of the marina and fishing boat area have been exchanged, with the marina now situated further south and the fishing boats relocated northwards. In addition, a second building with showers and toilets has been constructed beside the lower car park. Cafés and shops have also been introduced along the southern road near the lifeboat station. Furthermore, the former castle has been converted into a hotel, and the nearby public beach has become a private beach reserved exclusively for hotel guests. An additional dock has also been constructed, allowing more boats to use the harbour. Despite these developments, the northern public beach and the passenger ferry service have remained largely unchanged.

